tion of one resource, a plant must allocate more of its growth to the structures involved in its acquisition, and thus necessarily obtain a lower proportion of another resource. Professor Tilman presents a simple theory that includes this constraint and tradeoff, and uses the theory to explore the evolution of plant life histories and morphologies along productivity and disturbance gradients. The book shows that relative growth rate, which is predicted to be strongly influenced by a plant's proportional allocation to leaves, is a major determinant of the transient dynamics of competition. These dynamics may explain the differences between successions on poor versus rich soils and suggest that most field experiments performed to date have been of too short a duration to allow unambiguous interpretation of their results.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPlant communities. 0aVegetation dynamics. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh  aAgrostic scabra.  aAlopercurus pratensis.  aArtemisia ludoviciana.  aBerteroa incana.  aCarex muhlenbergii.  aCrepis tectorum.  aDryas drummondii.  aErigeron canadensis.  aFestuca ovina.  aGeomys bursarius.  aGrime, comparison with.  aHedeoma hispida.  aHolcus lanatus.  aLempholemma.  aLespedeza capitata.  aMicrotus pennsylvanicus.  aPanicum perlongum.  aPinus strobus.  aQuercus rubra.  aRosa arkansana.  aSetaria glauca.  anutritional isoclines.  atransient dynamics.  azero net growth isoclines.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691209593zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691209593423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691209593.jpg  a978-3-11-044249